Mirror OpenMW's in-game Hide UI toggle onto the Alpha3 second-screen overlay.

WindowManager::setHudVisibility(show) is the single entry point that flips
mHudEnabled when the player toggles Hide UI (bound to the "Toggle HUD" control).
It runs only on an actual toggle, not per frame, so it's the right place to
notify the app. We call companionDeliverHudVisibility() (defined in
androidmain.cpp, which is copied into the openmw build) which forwards the new
state to EngineActivity.onHudVisibilityChanged over JNI. The Kotlin side
combines it with the app's own isUIHidden preference to show/hide OverlayUI
(touch controls, gear icon, arrow) in sync with the game HUD.

We also call setCursorActive(mHudEnabled) here: with Hide UI active the
companion screen handles all interaction, so the top-screen gamepad cursor
(summoned by the left thumbstick over barter/map/service windows) is unwanted.
Toggling Hide UI off (mHudEnabled = true) re-enables the cursor.

--- a/apps/openmw/mwgui/windowmanagerimp.cpp
+++ b/apps/openmw/mwgui/windowmanagerimp.cpp
@@ -1806,10 +1806,21 @@
         mQuickKeysMenu->activateQuickKey(index);
     }

+#ifdef __ANDROID__
+extern "C" void companionDeliverHudVisibility(bool visible);
+#endif
+
     bool WindowManager::setHudVisibility(bool show)
     {
         mHudEnabled = show;
         updateVisible();
         mMessageBoxManager->setVisible(mHudEnabled);
+#ifdef __ANDROID__
+        // COMPANION: sync the Alpha3 second-screen overlay with the in-game Hide UI.
+        companionDeliverHudVisibility(mHudEnabled);
+        // COMPANION: disable the gamepad cursor while Hide UI is active so the
+        // thumbstick doesn't summon a cursor over barter/map/service windows.
+        setCursorActive(mHudEnabled);
+#endif
         return mHudEnabled;
     }

